R Notebook for Gulfstream generated dataset

Overview of the dataset

We have two datasets which simulate the Sea Surface Height (SSH) and the Sea Surface Salinity (SSS) :

library(ncdf4)
library(lattice)

nc <- nc_open("ref.nc", write=FALSE, readunlim=TRUE, verbose=FALSE, 
        auto_GMT=TRUE, suppress_dimvals=FALSE )

print(nc)

NAT <- nc_open("NATL60.nc", write=FALSE, readunlim=TRUE, verbose=FALSE, 
              auto_GMT=TRUE, suppress_dimvals=FALSE )

We extract the two arrays which are interesting for us

ssh <- ncvar_get(nc,"ssh")
sss <- ncvar_get(NAT, "sss")

The values of the SSH and the SSS are contained in a large array. The size of the array is 201×201×365201×201×365. The dimensions 201×201201×201 stand for the spatial dimensions (respectively latitude and longitude) while 365365 symbolizes the time. The simulation is supposed to cover an entire year and a value of SSS and SSH is simulated for each day of the year. We can visualize the heatmap of the SSH for the first days.

levelplot(ssh[1:201,1:201,1],xlab="longitude",ylab="latitude",col.regions = hcl.colors(30))

levelplot(ssh[1:201,1:201,2],xlab="longitude",ylab="latitude",col.regions = hcl.colors(30))

levelplot(ssh[1:201,1:201,3],xlab="longitude",ylab="latitude",col.regions = hcl.colors(30))

We can divide the space in three distinct zone, namely the upper, the central and the lower zone. Each zone correspond to different magnitude of SSH.

For given latitude and longitude, we also plot the annual variation of the SSH :

lon<-150
lat<-20
plot(1:365, ssh[lon,lat,1:365], "line", xlab = "time", ylab="ssh")

We have to be careful that the day 1 is not the 1st1st January but the 1st1st October. For consistency we should divide the year within different periods (winter, summer …).

We are particularly interesting in the way the time derivatives of the ssh behave. Noting XtXt the value of ssh at day We use the following approximation for the time gradient and laplacian derivative of the ssh :

∇t=Xt+1−XtΔt=Xt+1−2Xt+Xt−1∇t=Xt+1−XtΔt=Xt+1−2Xt+Xt−1

We create the corresponding dataset :

gradssh <- array( dim = c(201,201,364))

for (i in 1:364){
  gradssh[,,i] <- ssh[,,i+1]-ssh[,,i]
}

lapssh <- array( dim = c(201,201,363))


for (i in 2:364){
  lapssh[,,i-1]<-ssh[,,i-1]+ssh[,,i+1]-2*ssh[,,i]
}

We’re now able to plot the gradient of the ssh for the first three days :

levelplot(gradssh[1:201,1:201,1],xlab="longitude",ylab="latitude",col.regions = hcl.colors(30))

levelplot(gradssh[1:201,1:201,2],xlab="longitude",ylab="latitude",col.regions = hcl.colors(30))

levelplot(gradssh[1:201,1:201,3],xlab="longitude",ylab="latitude",col.regions = hcl.colors(30))

We can also plot the time variation of the gradient for a given location :

plot(1:364,gradssh[lon,lat,1:364],"line", xlab = "time", ylab="ssh gradient")

Modelling with GPD-Elliptical laws

A random variable XX of RnRn is GPD-elliptical if its density is of the following type

f(x)=cngσ,ξ((x−μ)′Σ−1(x−μ))f(x)=cngσ,ξ((x−μ)′Σ−1(x−μ))

with ΣΣ a definite positive matrix of Mn×nMn×n, μμ a vector of RnRn, c a normalising constant and gσ,ξgσ,ξ a real-valued function of the form

gσ,ξ(s)=((1+ξσs)+)−1ξσ>0ξ<2ngσ,ξ(s)=((1+ξσs)+)−1ξσ>0ξ<2n
where f+f+ denotes the positive part of ff. We usually write

X∼ϵn(μ,Σ,gσ,ξ)X∼ϵn(μ,Σ,gσ,ξ)

It could also be reformulated in the following manner :

X=μ+RA′UX=μ+RA′U
with A∈Mn×nA∈Mn×n such that A′A=ΣA′A=Σ, U∈RnU∈Rn uniformly distributed on the sphere unit and R∈R+R∈R+, called the radial variable, independent from UU with density :

h(r)=2∫∞0tn2−1gσ,ξ(t)dtrn−1gσ,ξ(r2)I[0,∞[(r)h(r)=2∫0∞tn2−1gσ,ξ(t)dtrn−1gσ,ξ(r2)I[0,∞[(r)

In the univariate case, n=1n=1 and Σ∈R∗+Σ∈R+∗ and A=Σ12A=Σ12. We focus on the univariate case when RR’s support is bounded. It is equivalent to consider negative values for ξξ. If ξ<0ξ<0, RR’s support is [0,σ−ξ−−−√][0,σ−ξ]. The upper bound will be written xFxF. Its cumulative distribution function,HH, is :

H(r)=B(r2x2F ; 12,1−1ξ)H(r)=B(r2xF2 ; 12,1−1ξ)
where B stands for the incomplete Beta function.

We wish to get insight in the extreme behavior of GPD-elliptical variables.In particular we will pay specific attention to the behavior of |X−μ||X−μ|.

For a given real-valued YY, we will write that Y∼Uϵ(xF,ξ)Y∼Uϵ(xF,ξ)if its cumulative distribution function have the form of HH with parameters \xF\xF and ξξ. We can easily check that if Y∼Uϵ(xF,ξ)Y∼Uϵ(xF,ξ) and α∈R∗+α∈R+∗, then αY∼Uϵ(αxF,ξ)αY∼Uϵ(αxF,ξ).For any univariate GPD-elliptical random variable X, |X−μ||X−μ| belongs to the family of UϵUϵ. ξξ and xFxF have different impact on the extreme for a UϵUϵ variable.

ξξ stands for the frequency of apparition of extreme events.For a given xFxF

ξ⟶−∞⇒Uϵ(xF,ξ)⟶U[0,xF]ξ⟶0⇒Uϵ(xF,ξ)⟶0ξ⟶−∞⇒Uϵ(xF,ξ)⟶U[0,xF]ξ⟶0⇒Uϵ(xF,ξ)⟶0
xFxF is the upper bound of the distribution and could be viewed as the intensity of extremes.

Examples

Let X∼ϵn(μ,Σ,gσ,ξ)X∼ϵn(μ,Σ,gσ,ξ), X=(X1,X2,...,Xn)′X=(X1,X2,...,Xn)′. As mentioned previously, we denote xF=σ−ξ−−−√xF=σ−ξ. We seek to characterize the differences in terms of extremes between the marginals XiXi and a given linear of the XiXi of the form :

Y=W′X , W∈Mn×1(R)Y=W′X , W∈Mn×1(R)
We keep focusing on the centered distribution, it is equivalent to set μμ to 00 without loss of generality. The marginals are then defined by :

|Xi|∼Uϵ(xFi , ξ~)xFi=(Σi,i)12xFξ~=ξ1−αξ,α=n−12|Xi|∼Uϵ(xFi , ξ~)xFi=(Σi,i)12xFξ~=ξ1−αξ,α=n−12

The linear combination of the XiXi is defined by :

$$ |Y|U(x_{F_Y} , )\ x_{F_Y} = (W’W)^{}x_F

$$ The parameter ξ~ξ~ is the same for the marginals and the linear combination. The frequency of extremes behaves identically.The intensity of extremes is modified.

Case of a ponderated sum

Suppose YY is a ponderated sum of XiXi, and the XiXi iid. In this case, Σ=aInΣ=aIn with a∈R∗+a∈R+∗. Because YY is a ponderated sum of XiXi, WW’s elements are positive and sum to 1. We can easily infer that xFY=W′WxFixFY=W′WxFi and thus xFY≤xFixFY≤xFi. The upper bound is reduced.

Case of the gradient

Let X∼ϵn(μ,Σ,gσ,ξ)X∼ϵn(μ,Σ,gσ,ξ), X=(X1,X2,...,Xn)′X=(X1,X2,...,Xn)′ with xF=σ−ξ−−−√xF=σ−ξ. We wish to compare the distribution of ∇t∇t and those of the marginals XtXt and Xt+1Xt+1.We now that the vector (Xt,Xt+1)′(Xt,Xt+1)′ is GDP-elliptical.

$$

(X_t ,X_{t+1} )’ _2(0,_2 =
(ΣtθθΣt+1)(ΣtθθΣt+1)

, g_{_2,_2})

$$

The absolute values of the marginals are defined by :

|Xt|∼Uϵ(xF(Σt)12 , ξ~)|Xt|∼Uϵ(xF(Σt)12 , ξ~)
We have the following transformation :

∇t=(−1,1)(Xt,Xt+1)′∇t=(−1,1)(Xt,Xt+1)′
Thus,

|∇t|∼Uϵ(xF(Σt+Σt+1−2θ)12 , ξ~)|∇t|∼Uϵ(xF(Σt+Σt+1−2θ)12 , ξ~)
In the particular case of of i.i.d r.v, the upper bound is augmented by a factor 2–√2.

#First attempt to model the gradient

We assume that, for a given location, the gradient have an univariate GPD-elliptical distribution.We plot hereafter the experimental cdf of the absolute value of the centered gradient

# Fonction de répartition empirique

Femp<-function(vect,x){
  l=length(vect)
  return(sum(vect<x)/l)
}


Fempgrad<-(0:100)
for (i in 1:101){
  Fempgrad[i]<-Femp(abs(gradssh[lon,lat,1:364]-mean(gradssh[lon,lat,1:364])),((i-1)*0.0008))
}

plot(0.0008*(0:100),Fempgrad,"line", xlab="Gradient of SSH", ylab="Empiric cdf")
## Warning in plot.xy(xy, type, ...): le type de graphe 'line' sera tronqué au
## premier caractère

A first idea is to hand-tuned the value of ξξ and \xF\xF to fit the empiric cdf.

#cdf of univariate GPD-elliptical value

ksin<--0.015
xf<-0.07

H<-function(r){
  return(pbeta((r/xf)**2, 1/2,-1/ksin+1))
}

#Initialization of the parameters

xfmin<-xf
E<-sum((H((0:100)*0.0008)-Fempgrad)**2) #mean-square error
ksinmin<-ksin
k<-0

#Loop to refine the parameters

while (k<200){
  xfboucle<-xf
  for (b in 0:200){
    xf<-(xfboucle-0.01+b*0.0001)
    Enew<-sum((H((0:100)*0.0008)-Fempgrad)**2)
    if (Enew<E){
      xfmin<-xf
      E<-Enew
    }
  }
  xf<-xfmin
  for (j in 0.001*(1:1000)){
    ksin<--j
    Enew<-sum((H((0:100)*0.0008)-Fempgrad)**2)
    if (Enew<E){
      ksinmin<-ksin
      E<-Enew
    }
  }
  ksin<-ksinmin
  k<-k+1
}
  print(E)
## [1] 0.03064377
  print(xf)
## [1] 0.0798
  print(ksin)
## [1] -0.058

We can visualize the cdf found using this technique (in red), and compare it with the experimental cdf (in green):

plot(0.0008*(0:100),H((0:100)*0.0008),"line",col="red",xlab="Gradient of SSH", ylab="cdf")
## Warning in plot.xy(xy, type, ...): le type de graphe 'line' sera tronqué au
## premier caractère
points(0.0008*(0:100),Fempgrad,"line",col="green")

## sera tronqué au premier caractère

A major disadvantage is the high dependency between the initial condition and the convergence of the algorithm.

Another technique is to use the theoretical moments of such distribution. We can prove that, if Z∼Uϵ(xF , ξ)Z∼Uϵ(xF , ξ), then :

E(Z)=xF(1−1ξ)B( 12 , 1−1ξ )Var(Z)=x2Fξ3ξ−2E(Z)=xF(1−1ξ)B( 12 , 1−1ξ )Var(Z)=xF2ξ3ξ−2
By using the estimators of mean and variance we could infer values for xFxF and ξξ.
